# Building a Parser Combinator from Scratch in Rust

Writing parsers is one of the most satisfying programming tasks. In this post, we will build a simple parser combinator library in **Rust** from scratch.

## What is a Parser Combinator?

A parser combinator is a higher-order function that accepts parsers as input and returns a new parser as output. The key insight is that parsers are *composable* -- you can build complex parsers from simple ones.

## The Parser Trait

```rust
trait Parser<'a> {
    type Output;
    fn parse(&self, input: &'a str) -> Option<(Self::Output, &'a str)>;
}
```

Our parser takes a string slice and returns:

- `Some((result, remaining))` on success
- `None` on failure

## Basic Parsers

### Literal Parser

```rust
fn literal<'a>(expected: &'a str) -> impl Parser<'a, Output = &'a str> {
    move |input: &'a str| {
        if input.starts_with(expected) {
            Some((expected, &input[expected.len()..]))
        } else {
            None
        }
    }
}
```

### Character Parser

```rust
fn any_char(input: &str) -> Option<(char, &str)> {
    input.chars().next().map(|c| (c, &input[c.len_utf8()..]))
}
```

## Combinators

### Sequence

The `and` combinator runs two parsers in sequence:

```rust
fn and<'a, A, B>(first: A, second: B) -> impl Parser<'a>
where
    A: Parser<'a>,
    B: Parser<'a>,
{
    move |input| {
        let (r1, rest) = first.parse(input)?;
        let (r2, rest) = second.parse(rest)?;
        Some(((r1, r2), rest))
    }
}
```

### Choice

The `or` combinator tries the first parser, then falls back to the second:

```rust
fn or<'a, A, B>(first: A, second: B) -> impl Parser<'a>
where
    A: Parser<'a>,
    B: Parser<'a, Output = A::Output>,
{
    move |input| {
        first.parse(input).or_else(|| second.parse(input))
    }
}
```

## Putting It All Together

```rust
let parser = and(literal("hello"), and(literal(" "), literal("world")));
let result = parser.parse("hello world!");
assert_eq!(result, Some((("hello", (" ", "world")), "!")));
```

T> Parser combinators are a great fit for Rust because ownership and lifetimes naturally express the idea of consuming input.

## Further Reading

- [Nom](https://github.com/rust-bakery/nom) -- a mature parser combinator library for Rust
- [Chumsky](https://github.com/zesterer/chumsky) -- a parser library focused on error recovery
